photo.title: DSC03961

description._content:
餃子的餡，用的全都是日本國內契約農場直送的豬肉和蔬菜。經過王將職人在店內一顆顆手作包出來的餃子，放進特製的「神之鐵板」中，根據每天的溫度和溼度，調整入鍋裡的水分，煎餃子時絕對不能掀開蓋子，一切憑熟練的技巧和敏銳的雙耳，透過鍋內的聲音來判斷煎熟程度，並以4分鐘之神速，完成一鍋燒餃子（煎餃）。
 這個「神之鐵板」是由熨斗廠商特製，所以能做到均勻導熱，以200度高溫4分鐘神速（一般煎餃鍋最快也要6分鐘），完成一鍋底皮如薄仙貝般酥脆，內餡多汁爽口，送到客人桌上剛好是96度的超完美燒餃子。

photo.tags: 宵夜 難波千日前 本家大たこ 王將餃子 大阪王將 元祖煎餃 餃子沾醬、味噌沾醬、檸檬塩味、辣油以及白芝麻 持もち帰かえり

photo.title: Day 8: Kiyomizu-dera, Kyoto Temple and Shrine tour - Japan

description._content: Day 8, Nov 11 2015: We enjoyed a 9-hour tour of Kyoto's cultural and historic attractions - We visited top city highlights such as Nijo Castle, Kinkaku-ji Temple and the Heian Shrine. - We explored the Kyoto Imperial Palace with our guide, once residence of Japan’s Imperial family. - We checked out the Thousand Armed Kannon and the legion of 1,000 life-size statues at the Buddhist temple of Sanju-Sangendo Hall - We visited the Kiyomizu Temple and enjoyed panoramic views over Kyoto from the temple’s terrace

photo.title: Tanuki lake

description._content:
Tanuki é um lago perto do Monte Fuji, Japão. Localizado em 
Fujinomiya, província de Shizuoka, e faz parte do Parque 
Nacional de Fuji-Hakone-Izu.


Originalmente uma área pantanosa, o lago foi criado em 1935 
para desviar as águas do vizinho Rio Shiba e criar um reservatório 
para uso em irrigação. O lago é agora um local de férias popular, 
com locais de acampamento, pesca, passeios de barco e é 
conhecida pelas suas vistas do Monte Fuji.

photo.title: Tanuki Lake

description._content:
Tanuki é um lago perto do Monte Fuji, Japão. Localizado em 
Fujinomiya, província de Shizuoka, e faz parte do Parque 
Nacional de Fuji-Hakone-Izu.


Originalmente uma área pantanosa, o lago foi criado em 1935 
para desviar as águas do vizinho Rio Shiba e criar um reservatório 
para uso em irrigação. O lago é agora um local de férias popular, 
com locais de acampamento, pesca, passeios de barco e é 
conhecida pelas suas vistas do Monte Fuji.

photo.title: Enko-ji

description._content: Camera: Sony A7 Lens: Sony FE 16-35mm f/4 ZA OSS PP: Lightroom, Viveza 2 Enko-ji is famous for its fall foliage. Even though we arrived early to avoid the crowds, the place filled up quickly. Getting a shot without people in the garden view room took a lot of patience and possibly some help from a fellow Japanese photoghapher who I think ended up swearing at the people that sat down on the edge of red carpet after the room was cleared. Some people in the far background have been cloned out.

description._content: Camera: Sony A7 Lens: Sony FE 16-35mm f/4 ZA OSS PP: Lightroom, Viveza 2 Enko-ji is famous for its fall foliage. Getting a shot without people in the garden view room took a lot of patience and possibly some help from a fellow Japanese photoghapher who I think ended up swearing at the people that sat down on the edge of red carpet after the room was cleared. Some people in the far background have been cloned out.

photo.title: Fushimi-Inari Taisha - near top of Mt Inari

description._content: I have often seen photos of this amazing place which is on the outskirts of Kyoto. And it didn't disappoint. I didn't realise how extensive it was. At first it was packed with people but as the path climbed the mountain (Mt Inari), the crowds thinned and I was able to take some photos with few or no people. It was beautiful through the forest coming down the other side. Instead of returning to the entrance, we took a side track that took us to Tofukuji Temple - about an hour's walk - a good alternative to catching the train. For more information: www.japan-guide.com/e/e3915.html

photo.title: Encounter in the snow

description._content: Snowstorm in Tokyo Album Shimada was waiting the crossing light to turn green as he heard footsteps approaching. The sound of the boots in the snow stopped close to him, and even while looking forward he knew the man was staring at him. The traffic light seemed to take forever to change, and finally he had no other option than turned to look to him, the man’s eyes widened as he whispered to him “When you’ll come out of the storm, you won’t be the same person who walked in. That’s what this storm’s all about.” With license of Haruki Murakami

photo.title: Hakone Shrine Entry Torii

description._content: On a weekend day trip with my nephew's family, we visited Hakone. The first stop was the Hakone Shrine, my first visit to a Shinto shrine. At the entrance we passed under this Torii gate which led to a trail through a pleasant and very old forest with traditional lanterns all along the path. Wikipedia: A torii is a traditional Japanese gate most commonly found at the entrance of or within a Shinto shrine, where it symbolically marks the transition from the profane to the sacred More Torii info: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torii

photo.tags: japan shrine shinto hakone torii

photo.title: Soga Brothers Shrine

description._content: The feudal history of Japan is filled with stories of revenge killings (katakiuchi), with samurai revenging their lord, father, brother… The tale of the Soga brothers took place 800 years ago, and although so much time has passed, and the samurai are now long gone, it is still one of the most famous such stories. In Hakone, close to the Hakone Shrine, there’s a small but beautiful shrine, dedicated to honoring the memory of the Soga brothers. Source and more info: muza-chan.net/japan/index.php/blog/old-story-about-reveng...

photo.title: Hakone Shrine

description._content: Wikipedia: According to shrine tradition, Hakone-jinja was founded in 757 during the reign of Emperor Kōshō. The original shrine was at the summit of Mount Komagatake. The shrine was relocated to the shores of Lake Ashi; and its current form dates to 1667. Credit for establishment is also given to Priest Mangan, for pacifying the nine-headed dragon that lived at the bottom of Lake Ashi. The primary kami of Hakone Shrine are Ninigi-no-Mikoto, Konohanasakuya-hime and Hoori-no-Mikoto. Ninigi-no-Mikoto is, in Japanese mythology, the grandson of Amaterasu, who sent him down to earth to plant rice there. Konohanasakuya-hime is, in Japanese mythology, is the blossom-princess and symbol of delicate earthly life. She is the daughter of the mountain god Ohoyamatsumi. She is often considered an avatar of Japanese life, especially since her symbol is the sakura (cherry blossom). She is also the goddess of Mount Fuji and all volcanoes. Hoori no Mikoto, was, in Japanese mythology, the third and youngest son of the kami Ninigi-no-Mikoto and the blossom princess Konohanasakuya-hime. He is one of the ancestors of the Emperors of Japan. Source and more info: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hakone_Shrine

photo.title: A rainy afternoon at Ginkakuji, Kyoto

description._content: Ginkakuji (Silver Pavilion) is a Zen temple along Kyoto's eastern mountains (Higashiyama). In 1482, shogun Ashikaga Yoshimasa built his retirement villa on the grounds of today's temple, modeling it after Kinkakuji (Golden Pavilion), his grandfather's retirement villa at the base of Kyoto's northern mountains (Kitayama). The villa was converted into a Zen temple after Yoshimasa's death in 1490.

photo.tags: world travel japan japanese buddhism

photo.title: Hasedera (光山慈照院長谷寺)

description._content: The Jodo Sect (淨土宗) Buddhist temples in the city of Kamakura (鎌倉市), Kanagawa Prefecture (神奈川県), Japan, famous for housing a massive wooden statue of Kannon (観音). In the foreground is a bust of Kume Masao (久米正雄, 1891-1952), a man of letters who once lived in Hase and was active in leading efforts to revive the cultural aspects of Kamakura, a city he loved dearly.

photo.title: Negai Ishi, "Wishing Rock", Kawazu, Shizuoka, Japan

description._content: In Japan we believe that large rocks, trees, etc can have sprits from our Shinto beliefs. This rock has the rope to indicate that it is sacred, and if you throw a little stone within the rope here, you can have your wish come true. It's a little superstitious but also kind of cute, isn't it? photo.title: Komainu and Pups

description._content:
Taken at Shinagawa Shrine.

Shinagawa Shrine, originally built in 1187, is located along the old Tōkaidō Road, right outside the Shinagawa post town, which was the first stop out of Edo (Tokyo) headed to Kyoto. 

It is said that Tokugawa Ieyasu, founder of the Tokugawa Shogunate, stopped to pray here as he lead his army westward to Sekigahara where he won a decisive battle that gave him absolute power over Japan.

photo.title: Snow storm in Tokyo

description._content: Snowstorm in Tokyo Album February, 2014. Taken from the hotel room in Shinjuku. The heaviest snowstorm in nearly half a century in Tokyo and other areas of Japan caused a rash of snow-linked accidents, resulting in nearly a dozen deaths and injuring more than a thousand people. Up to 27 centimeters (10.6 inches) of snow was recorded in Tokyo on Saturday the 8th of February, the heaviest fall in the capital for 45 years, according to meteorologists.
